A corroded palstave&nbsp;of South Western type dating from the Taunton phase (c.1400-1275&nbsp;BC) of the Middle Bronze Age.&nbsp;It is incomplete insofar as no trace of a loop survives. The axehead&nbsp;has a solidly rectilinear butt which&nbsp;flares outwards very gradually as it develops into the blade, and ultimately a narrow cutting edge. In profile the butt end expands into flanges to give it broadly triangular sides;&nbsp;the stop ridge is deep which creates a distinctive &#39;H&#39; cross section&nbsp;(Pearce&nbsp;1983,&nbsp;29- 30,&nbsp;582).&nbsp;This axehead appears to be of &#39;class 2, group 1&#39; as&nbsp;there is a distinct central mid-rib on the upper&nbsp;blade. There is no decoration on the lower blade, towards the cutting edge.&nbsp;

Measurements: 123 mm in length and&nbsp;24 mm in width at the middle. The butt end is 20 mm and then flares to the blade end with a width of 39 mm. The weight is&nbsp;210.93 g

Where the surface patina survives it is a dark green colour, verging on black in places. Otherwise, the surface is largely corroded, with pitting in places.
